{
  "title": "Media of Social Memory",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "0f3bc5a8e3d429f1",
      "text": "If we deal with media technologies and communicative forms of remembering, then the focus is on the active engagement with the past oriented to current social circumstances and cultural needs for meaning. This, the premise goes, cannot possibly be undone or exactly repeated (Dummett 1964). However, the one past is not closed and told once and for all, but a multitude of retrospective references and thus pasts are reconstructed open to change in the respective present, from diverse positions and along different interests and liabilities. The past is not dead; it is not even past - this is how the basic assumption of the mnemonic turn could be summarized in the bon mot first formulated by William Faulkner in his play Requiem for a Nun and later taken up in Christa Wolf's novel Kindheitsmuster."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "18862bac7c9a3557",
      "text": "In today's societies, in which long-term future developments, for example of climate, population, or the economy, seem increasingly unpredictable, the past paradoxically becomes the actual space of possibility, open to new experiences and opportunities for knowledge. \"Precisely for this reason, its reinterpretation is one of the first official acts of new systems of rule,\" Judith Schalansky (2018, 19) observes, adding, \"Anyone who, like me, has once experienced the rupture of history, the iconoclasm of the victors, the dismantling of monuments, does not find it difficult to recognize in any vision of the future nothing but a future past.\" Remembering is thus not a one-sided backward-looking project, but retrospection implies diagnosis of the present and foresight (Koselleck 1979). More strikingly, Der Spiegel ran the headline on the occasion of Holocaust Remembrance Day 2019: \"Remembrance is the struggle for the future\" (Zadoff 2019)."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "5df2439f7a082041",
      "text": "In general, memory can be understood as the \"knowledge that guides action and experience in the specific interaction framework of a society and is available for repeated practice and instruction from generation to generation\" (Assmann 1988, 9). Accordingly, memory is not a static category, but only in active access are archived or canonized knowledge stocks made accessible to a memory-cultural debate, perpetuated and modulated (Keightley and Pickering 2014; Lohmeier and Pentzold 2014; Frith and Kalin 2016; Hand 2016; Burkey 2020)."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "864929e7d71f39a7",
      "text": "The concept of remembering then refers to the process of socially binding and organized envisioning of the past, which results in memories and in turn refers to them (Assmann and Hölscher 1988; Assmann 1992; Zerubavel 2003; Rossington and Whitehead 2007; Augé 2013; Lehmann et al. 2013; Dimbath and Heinlein 2014). The concept of memory culture, in turn, refers - despite all the differences in approaches - to conflicting memories and counter-memories by means of which social constellations of varying sizes, from nations to local communities, keep past periods, events, or persons in mind, visualize, or forget. According to Bellah and colleagues (1985, 153), communities have \"a history - in an important sense they are constituted by their past - and for this reason we can speak of a real community as a 'community of memory,' one that does not forget its past. In order not to forget that past, a community is involved in retelling its story, its constitutive narrative\". At the same time, communalization can also imply the rejection of contrary versions of the past (Hobsbawm 1972). Collective memories here become a catalyst of social integration and reproduction, they create communality, and they are also used to demarcate affiliations (Winter 1995; Cornelißen 2003; Assmann 2007). \"Social memories,\" Sebald and Weyand (2011, 174) argue, \"are key to understanding the stability and dynamics of societies.\""
    },
